{"id":"1005.1243","submitter":"Elem\\'er Rosinger","authors":"Elemer E. Rosinger","title":"Rigid and Non-Rigid Mathematical Theories: the Ring $\\mathbb{Z}$ Is\n  Nearly Rigid","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Mathematical theories are classified in two distinct classes : {\\it rigid},\nand on the other hand, {\\it non-rigid} ones. Rigid theories, like group theory,\ntopology, category theory, etc., have a basic concept - given for instance by a\nset of axioms - from which all the other concepts are defined in a unique way.\nNon-rigid theories, like ring theory, certain general enough pseudo-topologies,\netc., have a number of their concepts defined in a more free or relatively\nindependent manner of one another, namely, with {\\it compatibility} conditions\nbetween them only. As an example, it is shown that the usual ring structure on\nthe integers $\\mathbb{Z}$ is not rigid, however, it is nearly rigid.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 May 2010 05:46:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 10 May 2010 08:35:14 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 12 May 2010 14:21:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-05-13"}
